VIBRIO PARAHAEMOLYTICUS - TAIWAN: BACKGROUND
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Vibrio parahaemolyticus, shellfish - Taiwan 990526225017
Date: Fri, 28 May 1999 07:50:14 +0300
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following background data on Vibrio parahaemolyticus in Taiwan were
extracted from the GIDEON software program:
- Infection is most common during April to November.
- 197 outbreaks (8,967 cases) were reported during 1986 to 1995, accounting
for 35.5 of food-related outbreaks during this period.
- 35 outbreaks were registered in 1994 and 46 in 1995. The 'black Friday
outbreak' (October 13, 1995) involved 2,175 students and seven primary
schools in Taipei -
contaminated fried eggs implicated.
- No fatal cases of V. parahaemolyticus infection have been reported in
Taiwan (to 1998).
- Over 200 outbreaks were reported in 1997, including an outbreak of 146
cases acquired from boxed lunches.
--
Dr. Steve Berger
e-mail: mberger@post.tau.ac.il
